SYPHILIS - CANADA (02): (MANITOBA) INCREASED INCIDENCE, METHAMPHETAMINE, INJECTION DRUG USE, WOMEN, CONGENITAL SYPHILIS
***********************************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Mon 25 Feb 2019
Source: The Star, The Canadian Press report [edited]
https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2019/02/25/spike-in-manitoba-babies-treated-for-syphilis-substance-abuse-likely-factor.html


At least 10 infants have been treated for syphilis in Manitoba [Canada] in the last 6 months [2018-2019], and the public health office says the methamphetamine crisis could be exacerbating the outbreak. [See prior ProMED-mail post Syphilis - Canada: (MB) increased incidence, methamphetamine use, 2018 20190131.6287056.]

The number of people with syphilis has nearly tripled since 2014 -- to 350 [in 2018, reference 1] from 118 [cases of primary and secondary syphilis in 2014, reference 2]. For women, it's gone to 168 [in 2018, reference 1] from 16 [in 2014, reference 1] in 4 years.

Michael Isaac, Manitoba's acting chief public health officer, says women can pass the bacterial infection on during pregnancy. Isaac says substance abuse and a lack of prenatal care were common factors in many of the cases.

The province is urging people to practise safe sex and to get tested. Women should seek regular prenatal medical care, especially if they are intravenous drug users. "I think the injection drug use that we are seeing in Manitoba certainly is linked with crystal methamphetamine use," Isaac said [Mon 25 Feb 2019]. "And we've noted that some of the moms with congenital syphilis have been using crystal meth and injecting drugs."

Winnipeg's police chief has said the skyrocketing use of meth is creating a crisis for police, treatment centres, and healthcare services. The Addictions Foundation of Manitoba has said meth use increased by more than 100 per cent in adults and nearly 50 per cent in youth since 2014. Isaac said the rise in injection drug use is linked to the increase in blood-borne illnesses such as syphilis.

Syphilis can have a wide range of symptoms that can be confused with other conditions. Tests confirm whether a person has the infection and, once diagnosed, it is easily treated with penicillin.

