******
[2]
Date: Mon 25 Feb 2019
Source: Winnipeg Sun [edited]
https://winnipegsun.com/news/news-news/syphilis-outbreak-in-manitoba-puts-women-and-babies-at-risk


The number of women and babies infected with syphilis recently rose in Manitoba, as an outbreak continues.

The province says one congenital case of the sexually transmitted infection, in which a baby was infected during pregnancy or childbirth, took place in 2015. That marked the 1st congenital case throughout the province in "many years," said Dr Michael Isaac, the province's acting chief public health officer. Another single congenital syphilis case was recorded in 2017. Then, in the last 6 months, at least 10 more infants were treated for syphilis, Isaac said. "We noticed in late 2018 and early 2019, a large increase in cases of congenital syphilis, especially in the last 6 weeks. The risk level has changed," he said.

Congenital cases of the infection can cause birth defects, miscarriage, stillbirth and other serious complications. While most syphilis cases in babies were found in the Northern and Winnipeg health regions, Isaac said the entire province is at risk. "I think the risk for congenital syphilis is really high across the province," he said. The doctor said 70% of the congenital cases involved pregnant women who used substances or injected drugs and 30% involved women who lacked prenatal care, though some cases didn't involve those risk factors. In Manitoba, every pregnant woman who seeks full prenatal care is tested for syphilis at least once.

Manitoba's syphilis outbreak began in 2014 but the spread of the infection has since increased between heterosexual partners. Before that change, the infection mostly occurred in urban areas and mostly affected men who have sex with men, said Isaac.

The number of women infected with syphilis jumped from 16 in 2014 to 168 in 2018, the province says. During the same period, the number of total syphilis cases rose from 118 to more than 350. Those numbers are expected to rise once again, as case reports are finalized, Isaac added.

The health officer said a surge in injection drug use, including crystal meth, appears to be related to the spread. "I think the injection drug use we're seeing in Manitoba certainly is linked with crystal methamphetamine use ... That certainly could be exacerbating the situation," said Isaac.

Syphilis can be cured with antibiotics. To reduce the risk of congenital cases, pregnant women are urged to seek regular prenatal care that includes a syphilis test. Those who have multiple sexual partners, have sex with someone who has multiple sexual partners, have sex without protection, and/or use intravenous drugs should be tested more often, according to Manitoba Health. If women with syphilis are tested and treated early in pregnancy, their babies are less likely to be severely affected by the infection, the province says.

