[The 1st news report above characterizes syphilis as a blood-borne illness and links its increased incidence to the rise in injection drug use in Manitoba, Canada. Blood-borne pathogens are microorganisms that are present in the blood stream that can be transmitted to other people by means of blood. There are many different blood-borne pathogens that include HIV, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, and syphilis. These diseases can be transmitted by transfusion of blood, although transmission of syphilis in this manner is rare in developed countries. Syphilis is most commonly transmitted through close skin-to-skin contact with an infected lesion during oral, vaginal, or anal sex.

Syphilis is caused by _Treponema pallidum_, a spirochete bacterium. _T. pallidum_ bacteremia, which occurs during primary, secondary, and latent syphilis, can result in transplacental transmission of this organism to the fetus during pregnancy, causing congenital syphilis, and an increase in the incidence of primary and secondary syphilis in women in the population is commonly accompanied by increasing rates of congenital syphilis.

It may also be possible to acquire syphilis by an injecting drug user who shares a contaminated needle/syringe with somebody who is infected (https://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/archive/newsrel/health/04-28TransmissionSyphilis.asp), but more likely the infection is acquired by the practice of exchanging drugs for sex and high-risk sexual behaviors, such as multiple partners and inconsistent condom use (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9147154, https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/68/wr/mm6806a4.htm).

The linkage of illicit drug use and syphilis transmission is reminiscent of the increase in syphilis among heterosexuals during the crack cocaine epidemic of the 1980s and 1990s, when the practice of trading sex with multiple partners for drugs, especially crack cocaine, played a major role in the transmission of syphilis. Under these circumstances, the identities of sex partners are often unknown, which weakens the traditional syphilis-control strategy of partner notification. - Mod.ML

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Manitoba, Canada: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6354666,261]
